[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2NT bid invites you to bid game if you have a maximum hand. Your 17 points is certainly a maximum so you bid 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \S6. Will you take your \SA immediately? or at trick 2? or trick 3?

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 3 : \C = 0 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more tricks, and they must come from \Cs. So you must drive out the \CA. The problem is that when the defenders win the \CA they may also take 4 \S tricks.

While you cannot guarantee the contract you can at least give yourself a better chance by holding up your \SA on the first trick, and also on West's \S continuation. You win the third \S with your \SA. 

Now you drive out the \CA. There are four possibilities:East may win the \CA and cash two more \Ss, down 1. East may win the \CA and cash just one \Ss, you make it. West may win the \CA and have a fourth \S to lead, you make it. West may win the \CA and be out of \Ss, you make it.

If you win the first or second \S trick you will fail. When you attack \Cs, West will win the \CA and play a \S.

Holding up twice can never hurt, and in this case it is the only way to make the contract.}
[Play "W"]S6

